INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3000','letter','1776-07-15','Fort Montgomery','NY','US','George','Clinton','','George','Washington','','individual','','At the same time I issued orders to all the regiments in my brigade, to stand ready to march on a moment\'s warning, and despatched expresses to all owners of sloops and boats twenty miles up the west side of the river','ltr_gec3000.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3001','letter','1777-07-26','Fort Montgomery','NY','US','George','Clinton','','George','Washington','','individual','','When I had the pleasure of seeing your Excellency at Ramapo, I mentioned that the terms, for which the two militia regiments stationed at this post were engaged in service, expired the last of this month','ltr_gec3001.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3002','letter','1777-08-09','Fort Montgomery','NY','US','George','Clinton','','George','Washington','','individual','','I never knew the militia come out with greater alacrity ; but as many of them yet have great part of their harvests in the field; I fear it will be difficult to detain them long, unless the enemy make some movements that indicate a design of coming this way suddenly','ltr_gec3002.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3200','letter','1777-12-20','Poughkeepsie','NY','US','George','Clinton','','George','Washington','','individual','','When the enemy left the river, it was my opinion that as many of the troops from the Northern Department should be sent to reenforce the Grand Army under your Excellency\'s more immediate command','ltr_gec3200.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3201','letter','1778-07-24','Poughkeepsie','NY','US','George','Clinton','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have already ordered out one fourth part of the militia of Orange and Ulster to the western frontier of those counties, who will amount to near six hundred men','ltr_gec3201.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3202','letter','1779-03-18','Poughkeepsie','NY','US','George','Clinton','','George','Washington','','individual','','The Legislature, before they adjourned, empowered me to embody one thousand men for the defence of the northern and western frontiers, or such other service as I should judge proper to employ them in.','ltr_gec3202.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3203','letter','1779-05-18','Poughkeepsie','NY','US','George','Clinton','','George','Washington','','individual','','I was called by an alarm on the frontiers of Ulster county, occasioned by the appearance of about one hundred Indians and Tories, at Shendeacon, a small settlement in the gorge of the mountains, about twenty miles west of Kingston','ltr_gec3203.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3204','letter','1780-04-24','Poughkeepsie','NY','US','George','Clinton','','George','Washington','','individual','','I received the act of Congress respecting the troops proposed to be raised for the defence of our frontiers. Some considerable time will necessarily elapse before they can be embodied','ltr_gec3204.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3205','letter','1780-06-13','Kingston','NY','US','George','Clinton','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am apprehensive that the other three regiments (they having, previous to the receipt of your Excellency\'s order, marched to the respective stations mentioned in my brother\'s letter) will not be able to reach West Point on as early a day as might have been expected.','ltr_gec3205.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3206','letter','1777-10-09','New Windsor','NY','US','George','Clinton','','Horatio','Gates','','individual','','My guards fell in with, and took two spies from General Clinton, going to Burgoyne. One of them confessed, that his orders were to make all possible despatch, and inform General Burgoyne that he had got Fort Montgomery','ltr_gec3206.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3207','letter','1777-10-17','Marbletown','NY','US','George','Clinton','','Israel','Putnam','','individual','','For the rest, as your operations must be governed by circumstances, I can only inform you of facts. Kingston was burnt yesterday afternoon, because I had not troops to defend it.','ltr_gec3207.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3208','letter','1777-10-27','Pleasant Valley','NY','US','George','Clinton','','Israel','Putnam','','individual','','General Gates, in his letter of the 24th instant, gives me rea son to believe a large part of his army are on the move down each side of the river. Part of them had reached Hurley yesterday.','ltr_gec3208.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_gec3209','letter','1777-10-30','Fishkill','NY','US','George','Clinton','','','','','gates','','I have, therefore, only to add, that the enemy have demolished Fort Montgomery, and all the other posts in the Highlands, and moved down with their whole force towards New York','ltr_gec3209.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
